    <item>
      <title></title>
      <link>https://vardahagh.com/authors/admin/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 05 Feb 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://vardahagh.com/authors/admin/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;I am currently a Postdoctoral Scholar in the &lt;a href=&#34;https://jfi.uchicago.edu/&#34;&gt;James Franck Institute&lt;/a&gt; at the University of Chicago and a member of the &lt;a href=&#34;(https://scglass.uchicago.edu/)&#34;&gt;Simons Collaboration on Cracking the Glass Problem&lt;/a&gt;, working jointly with Professors &lt;a href=&#34;https://nagelgroup.uchicago.edu/Nagel-Group/index.html&#34;&gt;Sidney R. Nagel&lt;/a&gt; (University of Chicago), &lt;a href=&#34;https://mmanning.expressions.syr.edu/&#34;&gt;Lisa Manning&lt;/a&gt; (Syracuse University), &lt;a href=&#34;http://corwinlab.uoregon.edu/&#34;&gt;Eric Corwin&lt;/a&gt; (University of Oregon), and &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.physics.upenn.edu/people/standing-faculty/andrea-liu&#34;&gt;Andrea Liu&lt;/a&gt; (University of Pennsylvania). I am also affiliated with the University of Oregon and have spent a year of my postdoctoral work at their physics department.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In my postdoctoral work, I have studied various fundamental aspects of Soft Matter, including the mechanics of the jamming transition, memory formation in glasses, and training extraordinary function into soft materials. Training is a new and exciting paradigm in the manufacturing of materials-by-design that makes use of the inherent complexity and versatility of amorphous solids. I am particularly interested in the training of out-of-equilibrium amorphous solids such as glasses, granular media, proteins, and biopolymer networks since they are exceptionally versatile and are able to retain a memory of the changes they undergo.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I completed my Ph.D. work at Arizona State University under the supervision of Professor &lt;a href=&#34;https://cbp.asu.edu/content/michael-thorpe&#34;&gt;Michael Thorpe&lt;/a&gt; on optimization of the mechanical response in elastic solids.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
